"43949.518055555556"	"43949.524305555555"	"100"	"562"	"1"	"43949.524305555555"	"R_1oAO8wt5TNdsT6h"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"2305d"	"Yes"	">1 year"	"5 or more"	"31-40"	"Urban Metro area >300,000 (e.g. Cleveland-Akron, Columbus, Cincinnati)"	""	"Middle"	""	"Primary Care (please specify)"	""	"family medicine/express care/neurodevelopmental prediatrics"	""	"Scribe America"	""	"MetroHealth, main campus"	""	"Yes"	""	""	"Very helpful"	"knowledge of how a clinic works/pathophysiology/knowledge of the health care"	"Very helpful"	""	"A fair amount"	""
"43949.521527777775"	"43949.525694444441"	"100"	"348"	"1"	"43949.525694444441"	"R_1jpMn6adxPvUqsZ"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"4499L"	"Yes"	"7-12 months"	"0-2"	"45981"	"Inner Ring Suburban >10,000 (e.g. Cleveland: Lakewood, Cleveland Heights, Euclid; Columbus: Merion Village, Eastmoor)"	""	"Mixed"	""	"Specialty Medicine (please specify)"	""	""	"Urology"	"Other (please describe)"	"Not through a company"	"Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"in Columbia, SC - I worked for a private practice urology group"	"Yes"	""	""	"Very helpful"	"CTAC encounters are much easier since I have been writing visit notes for a long time. I also know a lot already about conditions related to male reproductive and kidney."	"Extremely helpful"	"I am much more comfortable in the room with a patient. I am not stressed out by writing the note and my CCE preceptors were very impressed by my skills."	"A fair amount"	""
"43949.523611111108"	"43949.525694444441"	"100"	"185"	"1"	"43949.525694444441"	"R_ApTd6uyrclndjtT"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"8201 G"	"Yes"	">1 year"	"5 or more"	"31-40"	"Inner Ring Suburban >10,000 (e.g. Cleveland: Lakewood, Cleveland Heights, Euclid; Columbus: Merion Village, Eastmoor)"	""	"Middle"	""	"Emergency"	""	""	""	"Scribe America"	""	"Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"Aultman in Canton, Ohio. Also worked family medicine at multiple different Metro Health sites and University Hospital sites. As well as geriatrics"	"Yes"	""	""	"Very helpful"	"Very helpful first year with terminology and typing during CTACs. As well as random bits during acute (since I worked in the ER, I had a general idea of how to treat / diagnose different diseases)"	"A little bit"	""	"A fair amount"	""
"43949.524305555555"	"43949.527777777781"	"100"	"329"	"1"	"43949.527777777781"	"R_32LazAnE0SZCx5p"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"1083 J"	"Yes"	">1 year"	"5 or more"	"31-40"	"Urban Metro area >300,000 (e.g. Cleveland-Akron, Columbus, Cincinnati)"	""	"Mixed"	""	"Specialty Medicine (please specify)"	""	""	"Electrophysiology, Interventional Cardiology, Nephrology"	"Scribe America"	""	"University Hospitals, main campus,Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"UC Health (University of Cincinnati)"	"Yes"	""	""	"Extremely helpful"	"The entire arrhythmia portion of our education this year was basically review, as with much of the kidney portions."	"Extremely helpful"	"Having a thorough understanding of how various physicians go about patient encounters helps me to spot the differences in clinical practice here at OU vs. real-world encounters - what works for one, what works for the other, things like that. "	"Extremely helpful"	"In a perfect world, I would nearly mandate medical scribing for those that want to be a physician! It was so incredibly helpful. "
"43949.524305555555"	"43949.534722222219"	"100"	"919"	"1"	"43949.534722222219"	"R_23W6cruF7oq4rcQ"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"1171M"	"Yes"	"7-12 months"	"45720"	"31-40"	"Other (please describe)"	"Urban &gt;70,000 (Canton, OH)"	"Mixed"	""	"Emergency"	""	""	""	"Scribe America"	""	"Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"Aultman Hospital"	"Yes"	""	""	"Extremely helpful"	"I have seen the impact more so in acute than wellness. I feel that it has helped me know which symptoms go with which differentials and the tests that you should use as more of a gut reflex than really having to study them. Additionally, when it comes to pharmacology, I have been able to think back to my time in the ED and associate the drugs that I know the providers used in situations with the drugs we are currently learning which helps me remember their use and MOA."	"Very helpful"	"I feel that being a scribe helped me to have a better sense of what was going on at my CCEs, even with things that we hadn't learned in class yet. For example, at my first CCE the doctor I was with started poking the feet of her patient with a sharp object as part of a well visit. When we left the room, I asked the doctor if she had been checking for diabetic neuropathy and she had been. We hadn't learned about diabetic neuropathy in class yet, so this was something that I learned in the ED. I also think that it helps me follow the doctor's line of questioning while in the room. As far as my leading the interview, I do think that it was helpful but I often find that I think of key questions that I know should have been asked during the interview after I am out of the room and/or while presenting to the physician. "	"Extremely helpful"	"I was initially hesitant about working as a scribe during my gap year. However, I could not be more happy that I did it. I had very little medical exposure before my time as a scribe and this experience opened my eyes. With all of the medical exposure and everything that I learned as a scribe, I would recommend it to anyone wanting to enter the medical field."
