"43955.613194444442"	"43955.618055555555"	"100"	"436"	"1"	"43955.618055555555"	"R_AvAKEe4YpDOmOsh"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"7223J"	"Yes"	"7-12 months"	"45720"	"21-30"	"Urban Metro area >300,000 (e.g. Cleveland-Akron, Columbus, Cincinnati)"	""	"Other (please describe)"	"Variable; some very affluent and others very impoverished"	"Specialty Surgery (please specify)"	"General, thoracic, colorectal, urological, bariatric, and plastic surgery"	""	""	"Scribe America"	""	"Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"Cincinnati Children's Hospital - Main & satellite campuses"	"Yes"	""	""	"Extremely helpful"	"During scribing, I made sure I didn't treat it as \"just a job\", but instead I learned all I could during shifts. I treated it as if I were a medical student (minus the hands-on contact). Many of the pathologies we study in-class I had seen in-person"	"Extremely helpful"	"Seeing how  attendings, fellows, and residents interact with patients has shaped my interactions. Patients at CCHMC responded to personable people, and that's something I aim for every interaction I have."	"Extremely helpful"	"Simply being a scribe does not prepare anyone. For it to count for anything, you have to actually learn on-the-job and be curious about the patients you see. I spend numerous hours outside of scribe shifts talking with attendings, shadowing, etc. to gain what I did from it. "
"43955.615972222222"	"43955.620833333334"	"100"	"401"	"1"	"43955.620833333334"	"R_b1naffJD54cf9jH"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"3030 MK"	"Yes"	">1 year"	"5 or more"	">40"	"Urban Metro area >300,000 (e.g. Cleveland-Akron, Columbus, Cincinnati)"	""	"Mixed"	""	"Specialty Medicine (please specify)"	""	""	"ENT, oncology, primary care, heme oncology, urgent care, genetics, "	"Scribe America"	""	"University Hospitals, main campus,MetroHealth, main campus,Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"Mount Carmel in Columbus (Hilliard, Pickerington, Westerville, Big Run, Trivillage), UH (Parma, westlake, minoff, landerbrook, twinsburg); Metrohealth (parma)"	"Yes"	""	""	"Extremely helpful"	"I know most of the labs/ imaging techniques we have learned, a fair amount of diseases, treatments, symptoms associated, etc. "	"Extremely helpful"	"CTAC- I already know how to write notes, ask questions of patients, pick which labs/ imaging to order, think about medical decision making. I also know how act in a medical setting, talk with different medical professionals and patients. The medical terminology has also been quite helpful. I am also way less timid than I would have been in clinical settings without my scribe experience. "	"Extremely helpful"	"I would recommend for every student interested in medical school. "
"43955.615972222222"	"43955.625"	"100"	"729"	"1"	"43955.625"	"R_2ZKPyHNtLofvIfg"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"3858P"	"Yes"	"7-12 months"	"0-2"	"21-30"	"Outer Suburb >10,000 (e.g. Cleveland: Shaker Heights, Beachwood, Westlake)"	""	"Low"	""	"Emergency"	""	""	""	"Other (please describe)"	"Centra Lynchburg ED- independently employed by the hospital but paid by physicians"	"Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"Centra Lynchburg VA ED "	"Yes"	""	""	"Very helpful"	"I know a lot of medics vocabulary that first years are not explicitly taught, but are expected to know. I also have an easier time reading journal articles/resources because I understand terminology. Working in the ED has taught be how to screen patients and what tests to order. It also gave me an understanding of  OLDCARTS and gave me conifidence going into my OSKI because I have seen it many times in the ED."	"A fair amount"	"I understand medical terms and can pick apart typical presentations (ie flank pain with painful urination may lead me to think kidney stone) my peers may have a longer list of differentials or not know that typical presentation. "	"Very helpful"	""
"43955.618055555555"	"43955.625"	"100"	"610"	"1"	"43955.625"	"R_272wGk8VK11ReH3"	"anonymous"	"EN"	"I consent"	"8733W"	"Yes"	">1 year"	"5 or more"	">40"	"Outer Suburb >10,000 (e.g. Cleveland: Shaker Heights, Beachwood, Westlake)"	""	"Middle"	""	"Primary Care (please specify)"	""	"Family Medicine"	""	"Other (please describe)"	"ABC Scribes"	"Other (Please describe, include smaller hospitals of UH/CCF/MetroHealth, e.g. UH Pharma)"	"Kettering Health Network"	"Yes"	""	""	"Very helpful"	"I remember and recognize many medications and their typical uses as well as some common side effects. I became very familiar with lab values and common testing modalities. I feel like I have a general knowledge of common diagnoses and how they are treated."	"Very helpful"	"I very comfortable navigating and reading most EMR's. I was able to witness and document many patient encounters and feel as though I have an advantage in recognizing patient presentations."	"A fair amount"	"Medical scribing was very helpful in gathering a clinical foothold, especially in family medicine I was exposed to several different disease processes, how they are tested and managed. Most of this is surface level knowledge and mainly pattern recognition but I feel as though I have some knowledge of the majority of common illnesses."
